social_posts.post_text:
The professor is in 😂 I spent the morning at @nyuniversity talking the power of sports and social change. The premise: effective decision-making, and responsible behaviors—is important in “getting the right things done” and in the right ways. This matters to sports leaders and professionals who are shaping the future of sports, today. 
Social Impacts and Community Benefits project is a team activity that requires students--working in partnership--to research, evaluate, write, and prepare a presentation about a current or historic event or transformation relating to the decision-making, practices, and policies of managing a major sports federation, league, team, or competition. Great students and great conversation. Such a pleasure.

I'll be speaking at the Africa Soft Power Summit, this May 23rd-27th, in Kigali, Rwanda! The Summit is the premier convening of Africa's creative and tech industries, as well as women's leadership, hosted in Africa but focused on growth for the whole world! Learn more: https://bit.ly/ASPSUMMIT23. @nbpa #womenlead
There is nothing like #Baltimore So blessed to spend #preaknessstakes with my favorite girl and photographer @sophiaablakee It was like a family reunion.
Rwanda has been unbelievable. I can’t believe this is my first time on the continent. Far surpassed all of my expectations.

New in the philanthropic space, I am in awe of the way he stands in the gap especially for young black men growing up without fathers. Special bonus, I got to cut up and hang out with @musiqsoulchild #mynewbestie He is wise and thoughtful and committed to our community. Someone should have warned him not to sit next to me. I’m likely to say anything these days. #nofilteratall If anyone has a good photo of me please tag me. I have been totally off my game. Living in the moment is not good for my social media feed 😆
Speaking of cutting up ….😆😂😆 I’m in the back row for a reason 😳Loved welcoming our @baltimore_links members with @blessedladydana and #MellasenahEdwards 💚💚💚

social_posts.post_text:
Honored to hear from special guest Colin Kaepernick about the work he is doing through his nonprofit, Know Your Rights Camp, at our Business of Giving program at UCLA last week. 
 
Know Your Rights Camp seeks to advance the liberation and well-being of Black and Brown communities through education, self-empowerment, mass-mobilization and the creation of new systems that elevate the next generation of change leaders.
 
Keep doing the good work Colin! And special thanks to NBPA Foundation Board Member Grant Williams for moderating such an amazing conversation.

Do you ever just listen to your body and your mind and say, it’s ok to hit the reset button. That was me this morning. I stood still and asked myself what would bring me joy. The answer, flowers. I took a long walk to the flower district with my playlist pumping. Browsed until I found the perfect collection of flowers and such. I took my time and created this beauty. I can say the reset button is in full effect. Back to work with a refreshed mind. What brings you joy? #joyseekersonly #flowerpower #fridayeve

Executive Director of the NBPA Foundation @stephanierawlingsblake explains the level of influence athletes have in our communities 🏀🏠

Minnesota, your warmth and hospitality touched my heart. It was an honor to speak at the Minnesota Association of Black Lawyers Scholarship Gala about the NBPA Foundation and finding your coach in philanthropy, life and business this weekend.

On Monday I also took the opportunity to connect, learn, and share ideas with the Timberwolves about the power of sports to affect positive change and the resources we offer players to support their community impact. I am excited for what’s in store with Rudy’s Kids, KAT Team Foundation, and more as our NBPA members discover their philanthropic passions. Let's keep creating a positive impact in our communities together!
